# UDS Naming Framework

How we name things across UDS. This rule is the vocabulary contract.
Its partner — [`uds-design-language.mdc`](./uds-design-language.mdc) —
covers *how* each state, surface, and elevation looks. This one covers
*what we call them*.

The framework is opinionated by design. Each category has one
recommended answer. Picking names by hand for every new component is
how a design system drifts.

When a skill is unsure what to call something — a new state, a new
prop, a new region of a component — it should land on this rule first
and pick from the canonical vocabulary. Inventing a new word is a
last resort and gets flagged for designer review.

---

## 1. States

The canonical interaction and selection states every component should
think about when it's designed and documented. Names describe **the
state the element is in** — read each as "the element is ___" — so the
set stays grammatically uniform (Hovered, Focused, Pressed, Selected,
Disabled), not a mix of bare verbs and adjectives.

**The eight standard states**, every component reaches for these
names when applicable:

| Name | What it means |
|---|---|
| **Default** | The resting state. No interaction in progress. |
| **Hovered** | Pointer is over the component, not yet clicked. |
| **Focused** | Keyboard focus is on the component. |
| **Pressed** | Mouse-down or finger-down. Briefly. |
| **Selected** | This is the chosen one in a group of equivalent options. |
| **Disabled** | Interaction temporarily unavailable. |
| **Loading** | Waiting for something to finish. |
| **Error** | Validation failed or something went wrong. |

**Four conditional states**, only used when the component supports them:

| Name | What it means |
|---|---|
| **Empty** | The component has nothing to display yet — empty table, empty dropdown, empty search results. |
| **Read-only** | The user can see the value but can't change it. The system owns it. |
| **Dragged** | The component is being dragged. |
| **Indeterminate** | A mixed / partial state — e.g. a parent checkbox whose children are only partly checked. |

**Two reserved words** that should not get mixed up with "Selected":

| Name | What it means | Use it for |
|---|---|---|
| **Checked** | The on/off state of a form control. | Checkbox, Radio, Toggle. |
| **Current** | The active page or section in navigation. | Nav links, breadcrumbs, the current page in pagination. |

Do not call a toggle's on-state "Selected". Do not call the current
nav item "Selected" or "Active". The distinction matters because
"Selected" already means *one chosen item among equivalent options* —
which is what a dropdown option, a chip, or a tab is. A toggle is on
or off, not chosen. A nav link is the current page, not chosen.

This split mirrors what the web platform already calls these things,
so what designers write on a Figma variant and what shows up in code
agree.

### Progress / sequence position (Upcoming · Current · Complete)

A small reserved set for components that show a position in a
sequence — a Stepper's steps, a multi-step wizard, a checkout
progress indicator. These describe **where a step sits in a
process**, not how an element is reacting to interaction, so they
live on their OWN axis (name it `progress`), never folded into the
`State` axis:

| Name | What it means |
|---|---|
| **Upcoming** | A step the user hasn't reached yet. |
| **Current** | The step the user is on now. (Same word as the nav `Current` — the active one in a sequence.) |
| **Complete** | A step the user has finished. |

A step can *also* carry a real interaction or validity State at the
same time — a `Current` step that has a validation `Error`, an
`Upcoming` step that's `Disabled` in a linear flow. That's why the
two are separate axes: `progress` answers "where in the sequence,"
`State` answers "how is it reacting, is it valid." Don't fold
`Error` / `Disabled` into the progress axis, and don't rename a
progress value to an interaction state. The Stepper's step is the
reference implementation — `progress` (Upcoming · Current · Complete)
× `State` (Default · Error · Disabled).

### The adjective form ("state the element is in")

State names use the past-participle / adjective form so every one reads
as "the element is ___": Hovered, Focused, Pressed, Selected, Checked,
Disabled, Dragged. That's why it's **Hovered / Focused**, not Hover /
Focus — the bare verbs read as unfinished and fail the "is ___" test.

Event names are the opposite — present tense, see §7 — because an event
is a *moment*, not a *condition*: the `focus` event is what puts the
element into the `Focused` state. Don't conflate the two layers.

### Why this set — and how it maps to Material

Material, Carbon, and Polaris converge on this set with minor wording
differences. The Material cross-walk:

| UDS | Material | Note |
|---|---|---|
| **Hovered** | Hovered | Material's component docs use the same adjective form |
| **Focused** | Focused | same |
| **Pressed** | Pressed (a.k.a. Press) | same |
| **Selected** | Selected | one chosen among mutually-exclusive options |
| **Checked** | Checked | on/off of a toggleable control (checkbox, radio, switch, multi-select segmented) |
| **Current** | **Activated** | UDS diverges on purpose — `Current` maps to the web's `aria-current="page"`, clearer than Material's "Activated" |
| **Dragged** | Dragged | drag operations |
| **Indeterminate** | Indeterminate | checkbox mixed state |

Our Design Language doc drew the Pressed-vs-Checked-vs-Selected-vs-Current
line in section 11 — this rule names the same distinction at the spec
level.

### Canonical values (the naming gate reads this)

A component's `State` axis values, and any selection axis, must come from
this flat set:

`Default` · `Hovered` · `Focused` · `Pressed` · `Selected` · `Disabled`
· `Loading` · `Error` · `Empty` · `Read-only` · `Dragged` ·
`Indeterminate` · `Checked` · `Current`.

A `progress` axis (sequence position, above) draws from its own small
reserved set — `Upcoming` · `Current` · `Complete` — and the gate
accepts those values on a `progress` axis. They are NOT valid on the
`State` axis (and `State` values are not valid on `progress`): the
two axes name different concerns.

Common drift → fix, flagged automatically by the naming gate (per
[`uds-figma-factory-quality.mdc`](./uds-figma-factory-quality.mdc) §2 and
the [`figma-component-inspector`](../agents/figma-component-inspector.md)):

| Drifted value | Canonical |
|---|---|
| `Hover` | `Hovered` |
| `Focus` / `focused` (lowercase) | `Focused` |
| `Active` | `Pressed` (mouse-down) **or** `Current` (nav) — pick by meaning |
| `Selected` on a toggle/checkbox on-state | `Checked` |
| `Activated` | `Current` |
| any lowercase value in Figma | Title Case it (§7) |

### One concern per axis (State is interaction-only)

The `State` axis holds interaction and selection states and nothing
else. Disclosure (open vs closed), content presence (empty vs filled vs
results), kind / mode, size, and tone are each their OWN axis — never
folded into `State`. A value that joins two concerns with a hyphen
(`Open-Empty`, `Open-Typed`) is the tell: two dimensions in one name,
and on the `State` axis it's always wrong (canonical states never carry
a hyphen). Split it.

The factory enforces this — see
[`uds-figma-factory-quality.mdc`](./uds-figma-factory-quality.mdc) §8
and the naming-convention gate's compound-value smell test (hyphen on
`State` = hard fail; hyphen elsewhere = soft review, since
`Parent-collapsed` on a `Kind` axis is one legitimate concept). The
global-search draft mushed `State = Closed | Open-Empty | Open-Typed`
into one axis; it was split into `Open` (disclosure), the trigger's
`State` (interaction) + `Filled` (content), and the popover's `Variant`
(content).

