## 5. Parts of a component

What we call the regions and adornments inside a component.

### Horizontal flanks (icons, prefixes, suffixes around text)

- **Leading** — the side the eye reaches first. (Left in left-to-right
 languages, right in right-to-left.)
- **Trailing** — the side the eye reaches last.

Used for: leading icon, trailing icon, leading element, trailing
element. Don't use Left / Right — those break in right-to-left
languages. Don't mix Start / End in with Leading / Trailing — pick
one and stay consistent. UDS uses Leading / Trailing.

### Vertical stacks (regions on top of each other)

- **Header** — the top region.
- **Body** — the main content.
- **Footer** — the bottom region.

Used for: dialog, drawer, card, data table, anything with a stacked
structure. Don't use Top / Middle / Bottom — those describe position,
not role.

### Single content region

If a component has one obvious place for content — a button's label,
a badge's text, a chip's text — call the region **Content**, or leave
it unnamed entirely. Don't invent a name where the convention is
"there's just one place text goes."

### Components with more than three regions

A few components have a richer anatomy that doesn't fit either
pattern — Nav Header has five distinct slots (brand, title area,
center, actions, account). Those components are allowed to name their
regions descriptively, as long as the names are consistent within the
component.

The rule is *consistency within the component*, not *forced fit*.

