## 7. Casing and word choice

Three small rules cover every name in the framework.

### In Figma

Title Case for everything a designer sees in the variant panel:

- Variant property names — `Size`, `Variant`, `Tone`.
- Variant property values — `Small`, `Medium`, `Large`; `Primary`,
 `Secondary`, `Tertiary`; `Hovered`, `Pressed`, `Disabled`.
- State names on a States variant property — `Default`, `Hovered`,
 `Pressed`, `Focused`.

Reading `hovered` in a variant panel feels under-set when it's
lowercase, like an unfinished label. Title Case is what Figma's own
asset picker does and what designers expect.

### In code

Lowercase with hyphens between words for the same names when they
land on HTML or CSS:

- `data-size="small"`, `data-state="hovered"`, `data-tone="success"`.

The rule: take the Figma name, lowercase it, hyphenate any spaces.
"Read-only" stays as `read-only`; "Loading" becomes `loading`.

### For actions and events

Present tense, single word where possible.

- `click`, `change`, `focus`, `blur`, `open`, `close`, `submit`.
- Not `clicked`, `changed`, `opened`.

This matches every JavaScript event name on the web platform.
Past-tense event names ("clicked") read as "tell me about something
that happened" rather than "when this happens, do something" — the
latter is what an event handler actually does.

