## 8. Component naming

How we name a whole component.

### Designer-facing title

Title Case with spaces between words:

- `Text Input`, `Text Area`, `Data Table`, `Nav Header`, `Icon
 Wrapper`, `Combo Box`.

Match how the component is named in plain English, not how it's
written in code. Material's component pages are "Date Picker", not
"DatePicker"; "Bottom Sheet", not "BottomSheet". UDS follows the
same convention.

### Code-facing id

Lowercase, hyphenated:

- `text-input`, `text-area`, `data-table`, `nav-header`,
 `icon-wrapper`, `combo-box`.

One word per concept, no abbreviations unless they're universally
understood — "nav" is fine, "btn" is not, "lbl" is not.

### One component or a family?

A button with three emphasis variants — Primary, Secondary, Tertiary
— is one component called Button. A text input and a text area are
two components because their underlying behavior is different (single
line vs multi-line); their layouts, key handling, and accessibility
expectations diverge enough that one component covering both would
hide more than it reveals.

The rule: components are distinguished by *underlying behavior*, not
visual difference. Visual differences are variants and properties.

### A family on one page (a base plus its container)

Some components travel together: a base component plus a container that
arranges instances of it. A radio plus the radio-group that owns
selection. A data-field plus the data-field-group that titles and frames
a set of fields. An accordion's item plus the group that coordinates
which one is open. These are a **family**.

A family is **one docs component**, not several:

- **One docs entry**, id = the family **stem** — `radio`, `data-field`,
  `accordion`. That stem is the `components.json` id, the folder under
  `uds-docs/uds/components/<stem>/`, the route, and the sidebar label.
  It documents every member tag together, the way `radio` documents both
  `<udc-radio>` and `<udc-radio-group>` in one spec.
- **One Figma page**, named after the stem (`data-field`, `accordion`).
- **One or more member component sets** on that page, each named
  `udc-<stem>...` — the base `udc-data-field` plus `udc-data-field-group`;
  or, when no bare base exists, `udc-accordion-item` + `udc-accordion-group`.
  A component's member sets are every non-underscore `udc-` set on its
  page whose name starts with `udc-<stem>` (followed by `-` or the end of
  the name, so `udc-data-field` doesn't spuriously match `udc-data-fielding`).
  The `figmaNodeId` deep link points at the **primary** member — the base
  if there is one, else the member the designer designates — and there is
  one deep link per docs component.

A member set is a public part of the family's API: it is documented as
its own tag. That is what separates it from a **subcomponent** (§9). A
subcomponent (`_udc-<parentId>_<subName>`) is a private building block,
only meaningful inside its parent, never documented as a standalone tag.
Apply the §9 litmus test to each member: would a designer ever use this
on its own? If yes, it is a public member set; if no, it is a
subcomponent of one of the members.

Two things this model deliberately avoids:

- **Don't split a family across pages** to "future-proof" a possible
  group or container. Related members share one stem page. Spinning up a
  separate page (and docs entry) for every base-plus-group pair is the
  sprawl this model exists to prevent.
- **Don't make a separate docs entry per member.** The group folds into
  the stem's one docs component, sharing its page, status, and changelog.

