## 9. Subcomponents

When a piece of a component only exists in the context of its parent
— a tab inside Tabs, a step inside Stepper, a crumb inside Breadcrumb,
an option inside Dropdown — it's a **subcomponent**, and:

- The subcomponent's Figma component-set node name — which is also its
  code / CSS token — is `_udc-<parentId>_<subName>`:
  - The leading `_` is Figma's private-component convention. It keeps
    the subcomponent out of the asset picker, so a designer picks the
    parent (`Stepper`), never the building block (`Step`), by accident.
  - `udc-<parentId>` is the parent's full kebab id — `udc-stepper`,
    `udc-data-field-group`.
  - The single `_` after the parent id is the parent/sub boundary.
  - `<subName>` is the sub-part's own name, hyphenated when it has more
    than one word: `_udc-stepper_step`, `_udc-breadcrumb_crumb`,
    `_udc-dropdown_option`, `_udc-data-field_example-longer`.
  The underscore boundary is what keeps the name parseable when the
  parent id itself contains hyphens: split on `_` and you always get
  `['', 'udc-<parentId>', '<subName>']`. In prose we still say "Step of
  Stepper" — `_udc-stepper_step` is the node/code name, not the spoken
  name.
- The subcomponent does not get its own page in the docs site, its
  own status, or its own changelog. Its anatomy, props, states, and
  accessibility live inside the parent component's spec.

### The litmus test

*Would a designer ever drop this thing into a layout on its own,
without its parent around it?*

- A single Tab without a Tab list — meaningless. Subcomponent.
- A single Step without a Stepper — meaningless. Subcomponent.
- A single Card without a Card grid — fine. Card is a component, not
 a subcomponent. Cards are dropped into layouts on their own all the
 time.

When in doubt, default to subcomponent and surface the question for
designer review. The cost of mis-classifying a real component as a
subcomponent is low (we promote it later). The cost of mis-
classifying a subcomponent as a component is a noisier asset picker
forever.

